{"questionId":"9066253","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">This question is about sodium and its compounds.</span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">The Born-Haber cycle for sodium oxide is shown (not to scale).</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img src=\"https://ib-questionbank-attachments.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/tinymce_asset/asset/5949/3d.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"391\" height=\"427\"></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Justify why K<sub>2</sub>O has a lower lattice enthalpy (absolute value) than Na<sub>2</sub>O.</span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">K<sup>+</sup> ion is larger than Na<sup>+</sup></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><em><strong>OR</strong></em></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">smaller attractive force because of greater distance between ion «centres» &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>[✔]</strong></span></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9066253","referenceCode":"19M.2.hl.TZ1.3d(iii)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Justify why K2O has a lower lattice enthalpy (absolute value) than Na2O.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d(iii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 15: Energetics/thermochemistry","15.1 Energy cycles","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 15: Energetics/thermochemistry"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}